  <caaml:metaData>
    <caaml:comment>Last avalanche profile for the season:&#13;
&#13;
Done at the crown of a windblown slab avalanche from 21.04.2022. Warm temps have melted the surface slab and the remaining crown is no more than 30-40cm.&#13;
The warm temperatures since then have stabalized this surface slab, and it is now well bonded with the layer below it. It does not slide during the compression test and it probably unlilely to slide from a skier.&#13;
&#13;
Trying to trigger the slide right above the crown (I stepped on top of it and was right on its edge) with skis required many jumps.&#13;
&#13;
Isothermal snowpack of 0 degrees celsius - warm temperatures and lots of melting. The surface snow slides a bit when turning with skis on this steep section, but this is only the very top part that has become soaked with water.&#13;
&#13;
Seems to be unlikely to trigger something deeper with the current state of the snowpack - the layers below are well bonded and progressively become less and less wet and more firm.&#13;
Another potential weak spot is around 1 meter from the surface, where after the compression test, sticking the shovel in the back and attempting to remove the column with my hands resulted in a breakup. At first the entire column started to be isolated (down to 180 cm from the surface, where the snowpit ends) but then a breakup was observed around a meter down. Still - this is quite deep and not likely to be triggered at the moment.&#13;
&#13;
Despite this - it is good to follow typical spring skiing rules and ski early in the day, before the water has a chance to soak the snowpack deeper down and potentially activate something more serious.</caaml:comment>
